      QA('Explain the Law of Variable Proportions with a diagram description.',
          'Introduction: It is a short-run law where one variable factor is increased while other factors remain fixed.\nStatement (Marshall): as the proportion of the variable factor to fixed factor is increased, the marginal product first increases, then diminishes and finally becomes negative.\nThree stages:\nStage I - Increasing returns: TP rises at increasing rate, AP rises, MP rises then falls. Producer does not stop here.\nStage II - Diminishing returns: TP rises at decreasing rate, AP & MP fall, MP is positive. Rational producer operates here.\nStage III - Negative returns: TP falls, MP negative. Producer never operates here.\nAssumptions: constant technology, homogeneous variable units, possibility of varying factor proportions.\nDiagram: TP, AP, MP curves with three stages marked.\nConclusion: Stage II is the stage of rational production.'),
